ul.li: Classify rules based on their typeâ€”whether they are prescriptive (specific requirements), performance-based (outcome-focused), or a combination of both.
Geometrical: Tag rules that involve spatial or geometrical constraints.
Model-Based Checks: Use BIM models to automatically check these geometric requirements against the specified rules
Spatial Requirements: Rules that specify spatial dimensions or configurations, such as the width of escape routes, the placement of fire exits, or the height of fire-rated walls.
Simple: Tag rules that can be evaluated with basic logical conditions.
Thresholds: Rules that require checking if a value is larger or smaller than a specified threshold (e.g., fire resistance ratings must be greater than 2 hours).
Binary Conditions: Rules that involve yes/no conditions (e.g., presence of smoke detectors in every room).
Enumerated: Tag rules that involve choosing from a set list of options.
Categorical Requirements: Rules that specify particular categories or options (e.g., types of fire suppression systems that are permitted).
List Checks: Compliance checks that involve verifying if the item belongs to a specific list of acceptable options
